        "text": "Parker said that he and the other creators of Facebook were trying to find a way to “consume as much of your time and conscious attention as possible.” In other words, they wanted to construct a medium that would get people [[addict]]ed—at least this is what Parker suggested when he continued to explain: “And that means that we need to sort of give you a little dopamine hit every once in a while.” The addictiveness should be as widespread and mainstream as possible, and not be built on something illicit or morally questionable such as pornography or gambling [⇒ [[Toxic Content]]]. As Parker candidly stresses, the idea was about finding and “exploiting a vulnerability in human psychology.” […] he should have said that he and his colleagues were looking to exploit not only a psychological but also a sociological and existential vulnerability. Ultimately, the “vulnerability” they homed in on was the human need to build identity—and to do so under postsincere and postauthentic conditions. This is what [[Facebook]] set out to do: provide a global online forum for everyone in the world to perform their profilic identity work."
